<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
This species was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Priesner, H" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin de la Societe Royale Entomologique d'Egypte" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 7" refId="B11" refString="Priesner, H, 1933. Contributions towards a knowledge of the Thysanoptera of Egypt, VIII. Bulletin de la Societe Royale Entomologique d'Egypte 17: 1 - 7" title="Contributions towards a knowledge of the Thysanoptera of Egypt, VIII." volume="17" year="1933">Priesner (1933)</bibRefCitation>
from Egypt, based on specimens collected on fallen petals of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Haloxylon" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Haloxylon schweinfurthi" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="schweinfurthi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Haloxylon schweinfurthi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It was first recorded from China (Ningxia Autonomous Region) by 
<bibRefCitation author="Han, YF" journalOrPublisher="Editorial Committee of Fauna Sinica, Science Press, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B4" refString="Han, YF, 1997. Economic Insect Fauna of China. 55 Thysanoptera. Editorial Committee of Fauna Sinica, Science Press, Beijing" title="Economic Insect Fauna of China. 55 Thysanoptera." year="1997">Han (1997)</bibRefCitation>
. Here, one female and one male identified by Han and four females and one male from Inner Mongolia were studied. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Priesner" authorityYear="1933" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Apterygothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Apterygothrips haloxyli" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haloxyli">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Apterygothrips haloxyli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from the other Chinese species by having major setae capitate at apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
